==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fehu'', from Indo-European ''*peku-'' ‘livestock, domestic animals’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''fia'', Old Saxon ''fehu'' ‘cattle, property’ (Dutch ''[[vee]]''), Old High German ''[[fihu]]'' (German ''[[Vieh]]''), Old Norse ''[[fé]]'' (Swedish ''[[fä]]''), Gothic [[𐍆𐌰𐌹𐌷𐌿]].  The Indo-European root is also the source of Sanskrit [[पशुह्]] ‘cattle’, Latin ''[[pecus]]'', Lithuanian [[pekus|pēkus]] ‘cattle’.
